These are really great headphones with really great sound quality, but after 4 years of daily use, the brackets that hold the cans fatigued and started to break. I'm not sure how many other people have these headphones, but in case the bracket breaks on yours, here's a printable replacement.
you will also need a couple washers (5mm inner diameter or bigger) and a small bolt and nut, per bracket. I believe the bolts i used were 1/8", but any size works (long enough to pass through and fit the nut on, but not too long to run into your head or catch on anything on the outside. any diameter, just drill out the hole to the appropriate size manually). the washers are spacers for the pins that go into the cans.
I also included the Solidworks file in case anybody wants to do some modifications to the design (you could easily print in the washer spacers for example) or in case anybody wants to use this to make this bracket for any other model of headphones. If you don't have solidworks, it would be a pretty quick change, so let me know the relevant dimensions (distance between pins, height of can, diameter and depth of holes, etc) and I can do it for you.
Cheers, and happy listening!

title: Replicator Gen 5 Multi-Spool Holder Assembly v1.2

description.text:
As a MakerBot reseller, we will be transporting our Replicator 5 to various conferences for demonstrations. I wanted some type of multi-spool holder that was easy to transport. This design is a first attempt, though I will be revising it soon. It is a combination of printed parts and 1" PVC pipe, painted whichever color you fancy. I went with red printed parts and grey metallic PVC. It is far from perfect, but for a non-design educated individual, it has turned out to be effective. The structure is designed to be flush with the back of the Replicator, however, I cut the upper PVC too short. I am currently revising and will post new photos when it is ready.

A few notes:

Each printed piece has screw holes. I recommend screwing the PVC into the holes for stability once you get everything assembled.

This was printed with .3mm thickness and 15% infill. If you discover a better combination, please post in the comments.

The top left bracket pin is not sturdy. I broke the 'handle' portion of it and just pushed the pin into the bracket. It seems to work well, though I will probably replace it with a metal pin the next time I get to the hardware store.

The top right bracket will require supports. I suggest printing this piece separately.

The spool holder inserts are not absolutely necessary, but I find they permit the spools to spin more freely.

If you are curious about the paint on the PVC, I used Rust-oleum Metallic Flat Soft Iron. I prefer Rust-oleum for all spray painting applications. http://www.rustoleum.com/product-catalog/consumer-brands/universal/universal-flat-metallic-spray-paint/

For the PVC, you will need a 10' length of 1" PVC. You will have extra, but that is good in case you need to redo some pieces.

PVC measurements (these have been revised, but not tested, since my initial prototype):
Lower legs - 9"
Upper legs - 10"
Lower cross-beam - 18"
Upper beam - 20"

This couples an iPod touch 4G to standard 23mm and 16mm tripod legs. This will allow you to secure a convenient mechanism to run iOS apps and control things that can be controlled with them through WiFi.   
This is similar to a version I created for a Lumia 920 - but as there is still no ad-hoc WiFi capability for that platform, I have been using an old iPhone. I realised I had an iPod touch that was not in use - and so now this has been pressed into service to provide the remote control for my camera. It can live in my camera kit within the holder, as there is room for the power charger to connect.

There are Rhino3D and STEP files of the design so you can adapt the model as you see fit. There is the added bonus of an iPod touch 4G solid model that you could pull out and use for other projects. The touch's are pretty much obsoleted by modern phones but provide a remarkably apps / WiFi enabled platform for tasks such as this...

description.text:
I'm very good at re-using things, and when my PrintrBot came in a box that was small, had a good base to hold the printer in, and seemed to be made of decent cardboard, I resolved to not throw the box away and instead use it when I needed to transport my printer.

The handles I made are inspired by plastic handles that connect boxes that computer servers come in. The handles have a 90 mm x 25 mm hole that is perfect for my L/XL male hands. Feel free to resize them in one direction if you need the handle smaller or larger (too much will change the wall sizes too much - it's not parametric).

Printer Brand:

No

No

Resolution:

200 micron (0.1984 mm)

10%

Notes:

I printed without supports. You can clean up the "catch" before assembling.

See the photos for assembly. Both flanges go in the same orientation: facing inside the box. Use the inside of the larger flange as your template - draw a line, cut precisely on the line (don't cut past the line or you'll compromise the cardboard). The goal is to have a snug fit so that when you attach the handles to a standard shipping box (3 mm thickness), you have to press the handle on and there's no slop.

DO NOT mate the two pieces with flanges facing away from each other unless your box has 12 mm thick walls (that would be a rather bulky box). See photos for final fit.

title: Twelve South HiRise Deluxe Insert - Apple Lightning Cable

description.text:
I love the Twelve South HiRise Deluxe for my iPhone 6s Plus, but the supplied third party cable broke on me twice. Instead of warrantying it with Twelve South (who have great customer service, by the way), I decided to switch to the Apple Lightning cable.

This insert is close enough to the original, which appears to have been pared down in order to save costs in mass manufacturing. Laid on its side, it prints in about 30 minutes. Standing up took me about 1h15m, which I chose because it prints the circular portion of the connector body a little nicer. Less worrying about overhang. Plus, this version has a bit of clearance just beneath the lip where the iPhone sits, so laying it on its side might make for weird prints.

I got impatient with printing the full length (this was the fifth version), so I canceled the print once it passed the portion which seats the connector body. The rest of the length is really for guiding the cable, which is entirely unnecessary if you ask me. The original insert doesn't reach to the bottom anyhow, so the full length isn't meant to provide any structural stability.

description.text:
My take on the Ramps 1.4 Box. V1 It prints in 2 parts makes it easy to print and fit your ramps to.
Im working on a couple of tweaks and will update once done. If you want to see more and how I create prints and 3D designs like this check out my YouTube channel.
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCSHUc93NXGwBacoIDDqPU2w

I had a look and tried to print some of the available designs and had trouble getting them right. My thinking for this is that the point at which you will print this your printer will still be a work in progress by the pure nature of the fact that you need a RAMP's box. At this point you may still have some teething problems like warping. I did this one with the idea being it should be easy to print and to assemble. I tried to make the design cope with warping that can happen in larger prints and leave it so it can be customised.
The newer version will have some additional bits like a break out for the reset switch and after printing it seems I can improve possition of some of the holes. The fan hole has a slot so the fan can be top mounted and the wires run into the box I did not put holes for the screws to allow as may fitment options as possible I may add slight resesses in a future design. The mounting posts can be cut down if you have trouble fitting it, I had to and have modified the design but have not yet reprinted the new one.

description.text:
Greeting Knob

"Welcome." Or, "Thanks for coming." Either salutation is appropriate with the Greeting Knob mounted on your door. There are two STL format files included with the Greeting Knob: the hand[le] and the mount. The mount is optional, but it enables a conventional door handle/knob to be placed on the other side of the door. Based on your choice of mounting technique, either flush or mounting it proud of the door surface, you might have to adjust the depth of the Greeting Knob's mount by trimming the attachment disc.

An ideal filament for making your own Greeting Knob is one of the many metal powder enriched PLA filaments. For example, the Proto-Pasta PLA metal compositions (proto-pasta.com) would be ideal for this print.

The illustrated handle was printed with Proto-Pasta Aromatic Coffee PLA--yielding a rich warm tone. The orange mount was printed with HIPS.

Vitals

  • Average print time: 3 hours (handle), 55 minutes (mount)
  • Supports: not needed
  • Brims/Rafts: not needed
  • Print speed: standard (Cura profile)
  • Software: created with Autodesk 123D Design

The mount might need to be reduced in scale (e.g., 2-3%) for securely holding the knob in place.

When using one of the metal composition PLA filaments, post-print processing might be necessary for obtaining a realistic metal finish. You can learn more about these techniques here: www.lulzbot.com/learn/tutorials/accelerated-aging-your-metal-bearing-3d-prints

NOTE: Greeting Knob is pull handle and NOT an operating cylinder doorknob.

This Cura plugin raises a print off the printer bed and places a support structure underneath it. This allows the bottom layer to be printed in a way that is more consistent with other layers.

To get the most out of this plugin, you should change the Cura settings so that the Initial layer thickness matches the layer thickness and Initial layer line width is set to 100. This way, Cura will slice the part with all layers identical and this plugin will lift the print off the bed, add a support structure under the portion that would have contacted the bed and continue the Cura built support structure down to the bed everywhere else. The plugin also gives the ability to set the Initial layer thickness and Initial layer line width to make up for the fact that those options were changed before applying the plugin.

Note: The stl file is just an example where using the plugin allows you to get rid of a flat spot on the bottom of a print.

Some amazing designs came in, but we had no people available with CAD skills to convert these sketches into 3D models. My appeal to all of you in the thingiverse community is to see the sketches and convert some of them into workable printable 3D models, so that we can have them printed and put in the East and West coast Project Shellter aquariums. Some other ideas were put up by some participants whose drawing skills were not as rich as their imagination: one girl wanted a shell in the shape of a plant-pot, which could grow seaweed for camouflage, another shell was in the shape of a piece of coral reef so that when the crab hides it looks like coral reef debris. author: boxplyer

description.text:
A colleague of mine, a geography teacher, retired this year. As he has always been a big fan of the landscape of Zuid-Limburg, a province of The Netherlands situated in the south of the country, I thought I would make him a 3d-print of the landscape. It is the only area in The Netherlands that is not flat. I did a search on Thingiverse, but it appeared that nobody had ever made a map like this before. Although there were many instructions on how to make one, I felt that I had to dig deeper. I did find OmNomNom Creator there; a program capable of creating surface maps out of grayscale pictures. However, I needed a contour map of Zuid-Limburg for that. After looking a bit further, I found a brilliant website by the Dutch Waterschappen. They had transferred data of all measured heights in The Netherlands onto a map. The best thing about it was the fact that you could even change the colours of the map! So, I zoomed in on Zuid-Limburg and made a grayscale map. After that, it was easy. I made a screenshot, some simple changes in Photoshop, (I made the surroundings completely white and removed some artifacts), dragged and dropped it into OmNomNom Creator, chose the right parameters and started the conversion. It then opened in OpenScad. It took some time to compile and render it, about 15 minutes. Then I saved it as an STL-file. This took some time too, and if you’re trying this, don't stop the program! The STL-file is very large: more than 26 MB. I uploaded it into Cura and about two hours later, it came out great on our Ultimaker.
The best thing about it? My colleague liked it! Blog in Dutch Thank you, Ilja Klink.

OK, the STL will be useless to anyone not soldering my particular board but the idea might inspire others to make their own.
I have 10 boards to solder this weekend.  There are various SMD parts and a bunch of through hole parts.  It can be a real pain to solder the through-holes while keeping them straight up and down.  So I created this holder.  I have pockets in the holder that all my through holes parts sit in.  They are positioned exactly for the board both in XY coordinates and the height of each pocket brings the part flush to the board.  Because there isn't any play in the pockets and because the parts sit against the board, all the parts come out perfectly vertical.
It takes about 5 seconds to populate the holder and put a blank PCB on top of them.  Then it's just a matter of soldering each pin which is a lot faster than the previous way of trying to hold a piece, soldering a single pin, checking to make sure the part is straight and then finishing the rest of the pins, then repeat on another part.
I also designed my board so that all SMD parts (except one pesky 0402 LED) are on the bottom.  This makes it really easy to solder the board in one go.  My production time has gone down from 10 minutes to about 2 minutes
I also put a lossely folded up piece of paper in each pocket.  This acts as a sort of spring and helps to push flatten the parts against the PCB.
Measure your board, draw up a design and print.

description.text:
After gotten some inspiration from an rc forum I made this, it's a tool to help you get the links and shocks for your rc car just right.
For links just mount them in the device and the anglethingie shows how close or far from having them the right length.
If you want to check your skock mount them in the device and push down on the slider, if there are any difference in springrate the anglethingie will move towards the side with the softer spring. This device have been tested with soft crawler shocks, I'm not sure how it will cope with on road or buggy shocks
I've deliberately made it without any more markings than center marking to allow for easier overview and if you for any reason want to make your own markings there's plenty of clean space for that

After you've printer just put a m4 screw through the "bricka" and put the bricka in the anglethingie and then mount it all to the ruler like seen in the picture with a nut on the underside of the ruler, and if you have any questions just let me know and I'll try to help.

And try not to mind the bad surface in the picture, my printbed apparently have some dents in it :D

The fitting for the slider are quite tight to eliminate any misreadings because of it moving around so make sure you set up your printer for high resolution print
I managed to squeeze all the parts in on my printbed, putting the bricka and ruler upside down and the slider pointing up but you know your printer best and print whatever way suits your machine
